# Render layer (Babylon.js)

This is the **only** place Babylon.js may be imported. It renders sim state; it
never owns sim state.

## Rules
- Render is a **read-only view**. It reads `World`/sim state and updates the mesh.
  It must not contain game rules or mutate sim state.
- The hex-globe is a **Goldberg polyhedron** via `CreateGoldberg`. It always has
  exactly 12 pentagons — this is mathematically unavoidable, not a bug.
- Orient the globe so two pentagons sit at the poles; the render layer exposes
  which faces are pole caps so `core` can tag `isPoleCap`. Pole caps are still
  drawn but excluded from simulation.
- Per-tile color: use the Goldberg per-face color API / a color buffer keyed by
  face index. Maintain one authoritative `faceIndex ↔ tileId` map; everything
  else derives from it.
- Picking: pointer pick → faceIndex → tileId via that map. Don't hand-roll
  raycasting if Babylon's pick gives the face.
- Keep camera (ArcRotateCamera), lights, and engine setup in `SceneSetup`.

## Performance
- Tiles share one mesh; do **not** create one mesh per hex. Color via the face
  buffer, not per-tile materials.
- The render loop runs at display rate; it reads the latest committed sim buffer.
  Sim ticks advance on their own cadence (or on HUD step). Don't couple them.
